1

00:00:01,899  -->  00:00:07,209
So you saw earlier that hypothesis tests and confidence intervals are pretty similar.

2

00:00:07,209  -->  00:00:11,339
But you might be surprised just how similar these two techniques are.

3

00:00:11,339  -->  00:00:13,109
It turns out that if you are to do

4

00:00:13,109  -->  00:00:17,189
a hypothesis test that contains a not equal in alternative hypothesis,

5

00:00:17,190  -->  00:00:20,596
your conclusions are identical to a confidence interval,

6

00:00:20,596  -->  00:00:23,250
as long as 100 minus your confidence interval level

7

00:00:23,250  -->  00:00:26,655
is the same as the type one error rate in your hypothesis test.

8

00:00:26,655  -->  00:00:30,743
That is, if you build a 95 percent confidence interval,

9

00:00:30,742  -->  00:00:31,979
this is the same as doing

10

00:00:31,980  -->  00:00:35,924
a two-sided hypothesis test with a five percent type one error rate,

11

00:00:35,924  -->  00:00:39,000
and building a 99 percent confidence interval will provide

12

00:00:39,000  -->  00:00:42,909
the same results as a hypothesis test with a one percent type one error rate.

13

00:00:42,909  -->  00:00:46,469
With this in mind, many academic journals are moving away

14

00:00:46,469  -->  00:00:50,789
from hypothesis tests as they find the results are often misinterpreted.

15

00:00:50,789  -->  00:00:53,504
Instead, more and more confidence intervals and

16

00:00:53,505  -->  00:00:58,135
other statistics like effect size or machine learning techniques are being used.

17

00:00:58,134  -->  00:01:00,809
There is more information on effect sizes as well as

18

00:01:00,810  -->  00:01:03,705
a link to a free course in the Udacity Nanodegree,

19

00:01:03,704  -->  00:01:06,000
link in instructor notes below.
